<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFFER TO BUY LENIN MONUMENT REJECTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
KRAKOW, Poland 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Polish officials have rejected an offer by an Italian Communist to buy a statue 
of V. I. Lenin that was removed from a public square after violent anti-Soviet 
demonstrations, it was reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Robert Napoleone, a member of the Italian Communist Party who owns a Rome 
publishing house, offered to give the 30-foot monument "a place worthy of a 
great revolutionary." 
</P>
<P>
But the local government council in Nowa Huta, the industrial suburb built as a 
model socialist city in 1950s, decided that the statue "cannot be the object of 
such a transaction," according to the state news agency PAP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
