<P>
ANDREW YOUNG BIG ON YULE CARDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ATLANTA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Christmas is a special time, a time when one politician can spend tax money 
sending special holiday greetings, and another politician can complain about 
it. 
</P>
<P>
Mayor Andrew Young sent jumbo Christmas cards this year to 1,500 area 
reporters, ministers, supporters and public officials, including Lt. Gov. Zell 
Miller -- who just happens to be a candidate for governor next year, just like 
the mayor. 
</P>
<P>
The 9 by 14 cards, featuring a montage of Atlanta accomplishments, Young's 
smiling face and the legend "Municipal Leader of The Year 1989," cost the city 
a little more than a dollar each to print, and 65 cents to mail. 
</P>
<P>
"I think it is inappropriate to spend $1 apiece to send a Christmas card out at 
the city's expense," Miller said. "If the man is elected governor, what will he 
send out in 1991 -- a billboard?" 
</P>
<P>
The response from the Young camp? "What a Scrooge," said press secretary Lee 
Echols. 
</P>
</TEXT>
